DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(89)90029-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387889900291
AB  - An endogenous switching regressions framework is used to structure and identify the impact of credit on small farm food production in Nicaragua. The results which emerge weakly support the hypothesis that credit had a positive impact on production and could be expected to reduce the pattern of structurally unbalanced growth in Nicaraguan agriculture. However, the estimated impact is of a form which implies a process of differentiation and unequal growth in the peasant sector in the wake of the new opportunities afforded by credit.
