UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387889900321
AB  - In this paper, I examine competing explanations for the behavior of Latin America's current account in the 1970s and 1980s. After briefly reviewing the focus of various economists on internal or external factors, I outline a ‘financial breakdown’ view which stresses the role of the changing availability of capital during this period of time. I then turn to econometric work which: (1) establishes the plausibility of viewing capital availability as a constraint on the current account, and (2) offers some support for all three views of the determinants of Latin America's current account.
